content.description: Climb a low, steep crux, then tackle another bulge before hitting the anchor.

This route follows the face just left of

Between the Sheeps

. There are a couple crux sections ending in a gear protected corner that ends in the shared anchors with the route to the right.
content.protection: 7 bolts and small-to-medium gear for the finish.
content.location:
This is just left of the arete of

Between the Sheeps

.

content.description:
P1. Start up a vertical wall with good holds to the roof crux, which is a little awkward. Continue up some fun face climbing to an anchor on the right.

P2. The second 5.7 pitch is engaging for the grade and climbs through a couple roofs. Small cams can be placed between the bolts. Belay at a rap anchor at the top of the wall.

With ~20 draws/slings, you can link both pitches.
content.location: This is the first route on the far right side of the wall.

content.description: Nice 5.10 face climbing leads to a slanting finger crack (gear). Continue up past more bolts and good climbing.
content.location:
It is just right of the large dihedral of

Book of Sheep

.

content.description: Climb dubious rock to a crux bulge, then go up the arete to the anchors.
content.location: It is the fourth route from the gully on the left side of the Dihedral Wall.

content.description:
Start up some flaky rock to a steep crux section along the arete. The rest of the route is off vertical, technical, face climbing.

A 60m rope barely gets you to the ground.

NOTE: the route names for "Bostock From Little Bird" and "Till We Have Faces" were switched by accident in the guidebook.
content.location: It is the third route from the right of 5.7 corner.

content.description:
This is a fun, techy face.

Climb progressively more difficult terrain to a techy crux just before the ledge. Continue up the dihedral to anchors. The crux can be avoided by moving right to the arete.
content.location: It is the third route from the gully at the left end of the Dihedrals Wall.

content.description: Start on steep crumbly rock in a corner. After a low crux, the climbing eases to the anchors.
Nice face climbing leads to the roof. Turn the roof on the right, and head to the anchors.
content.location: This is the farthest left route on the Dihedrals Wall.

content.description: Start up a steep wall with a couple funky choss nuggets. Join the arete with nice rock and moves. After reaching the ledge, you can either lower or continue through a so-so bulge at 5.10b.
content.location: It is on the far left side of the Dihedral Wall just left of the 5.7 corner.

content.description:
Start up the lower face of

Bostock From Little Bird

, then branch left in the leaning corner system (gear) until you reach the bolted upper headwall. This is listed as 5.11a in the guidebook with the crack being the crux. I thought the lower face was solid 5.11 while the crack was 5.10d/5.11a.  It is a full value pitch that will stretch your 70m rope. Watch the ends of your rope!
content.protection: ~15 draws and gear from 0.2-2 plus small-medium nuts.
content.location:
Start up the bolts for

Bostock From Little Bird

, which is the middle line just left of the arete.

content.description:
P1. Climb a clean face to a crux bulge at bolt 3/4. Angle right after the bulge, and face climb to a finger crack. Follow that to its end, and angle left to the anchors. These anchors are shared with Nanny State (use a 70m rope for the lower?).

P2. A single bolt protects the 5.8 move above the anchors. Place some cams, and run it out to the anchors (5.5).

Both pitches can be linked easily. Add an extra 0.75 cam which protects getting to the last bolt.
content.protection: 5 (12?) bolts plus 0.3-0.75 cams and optional larger cams.
content.location: Start just below the larger boulder on the right side of the arete.

content.description: Climb the dihedral behind the big boulder, then step right to a big ledge. Climb the crux face above, then go up easier terrain to the anchors.
content.protection: 11 bolts plus an optional finger or thin hands cam.
content.location: This ascends the right wall of the dihedral behind the big boulder.

content.description:
This route has it all, a finger crack, liebacking, steep technical climbing, a pumpy traverse, hero jugs, and technical corner climbing.

Start up a moderate 5.10 finger crack with good trad protection. Pass a slightly chossy band and clip the first bolt. Some committing liebacks lead to the steep crux with good hands but poor feet. After the crux, traverse slightly right then back left to some great jugs on the arete. Finish on a tight, technical corner with small holds (5.11d).
content.protection: 11 bolts and finger-sized cams for the start (0.3-0.5).
content.location:
It is just left of

Entropy

and 6 routes left of the start of Dihedral Wall.

content.description: Start up the 5.7 dihedral (bolt), and continue up until you can step left in a thin crack. Follow a crack through bulge with 2 bolts. Stop at a lower anchor or continue to the upper anchor.
content.location:
Start up the

Book of Sheep

(5.7) in a large dihedral.

content.description: Hoof in the Grave is pretty tough and sustained. It is easily identified by the massive, detached section of cliff about halfway up the climb...don’t worry, it's not going anywhere.
content.location: This is the bolt line right of the huge, detached chunk of rock.

content.description: Climb dubious rock to an undercling crux, then go up the left side of the arete to the anchors.
content.location:
This climbs the arete left of

Roll the Stone Away

.

content.description:
This is another Sheep classic.... Start up the beautiful, brown patina face with 2 obvious bolts. Place a critical #1 cam at the break, and join the corner system until you can traverse right to the next bolt. Thin edging leads to the crux section (bolts 5/6). Tiptoe up to the good undercling, and figure out a way past the next moves. A couple more bolts leads to an anchor at 35m.

The hard parts are well-protected with bolts, but you might be running it out on easier terrain. Consider using a "locker" draw on bolt 3.
content.location:
It is just left of the

5.12 arete

....

content.description:
This is another McCorkel gem. Start in finger crack in a dihredal, then battle up a slightly obtuse dihedral system with stemming, palming, and arete moves for a long pitch. A 2 foot sling on the first bolt helps with rope drag.

Try not to get McCorkel'ed....
content.protection: 10 bolts and finger-sized cams for the start (0.3-0.75).
content.location: It is about 40 feet from the right side of the wall....

content.description:
Devo is a fun climb up the dihedral between

Bostock..

and

Face the Change

. Start with a tricky bolted section requiring some creative stemming, and then work into a finger crack that splits the top part of the dihedral.
content.protection: 6 bolts, a pin, and gear (small-medium nuts and cams to 0.75 or 1).

content.description: Crack of Lamb goes up the obvious roof crack on the right side of the wall. Climb up to the intimidating roof, and figure out a way past it. An engaging trad crack leads to a set of anchors.
content.location: This surmounts the roof crack on the right side of the wall.

content.description:
Clip the first 3 bolts of

Between the Sheeps

to the ledge. Step right, and engage the steep roof for 4 bolts. The crux revolves around a hard deadpoint to a finger bucket right at the end of the roof. Easier face climbing after the roof gets you to the anchor.

Thisi is an old project that had 2 bolts already from the PH Crew.
content.location:
It ascends the obvious meg-roof in the center of the crag. Located just to the right of

Between the Sheeps

, it shares the first 3 bolts with that route.

content.description:
A tricky start leads to an easier section before the crux techy face at the top. Climb the second bolt line on the right wall of the dihedral to easier climbing in a dihedral. Move right out of the dihedral and up the crux face to anchors.

Note that the names for Bostock From Little Bird and

Till We Have Faces

are switched in the guidebook.
content.location: This is the middle of three bolt routes on the right wall of the dihedral. See the photo.

content.description: Book of Sheep is a grungy corner that climbs better than it looks. Clip a low bolt, and move through a crack in the corner until the crack fizzles out. 3 more bolts protect the last bit to the anchors.
content.location: This is the biggest corner in the dihedral area, about in the middle of the wall.

content.description:
P1. Head up the slab behind the large boulder on the right side of the wall. Engage the

steep

overhang with good jugs to an anchor above the lip.

P2. A gear protected second pitch goes to a second anchor at 5.7.
content.protection: 11 bolts with gear for the second pitch.
content.location: It ascends the slab right behind the large boulder on the right side of the wall.

content.description: This is a Sheep Mountain classic! Head up the open book, and engage the pumpy overhangs. Traverse right to the arete, and follow that through a couple small overlaps to the anchors. An optional green Alien can be placed along the way.
content.protection: 11 bolts with an optional green Alien.
content.location: This ascends the first arete feature on the right side of the wall.
